(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
=== 1AC Prolif ===

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== Contention One: Prolif ====

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== Global nuclear renaissance makes proliferation and weaponization likely without nuclear leadership ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**Hamre and Sowcroft 2012**(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) (John Hamre, President and CEO, Center for Strategic and International Studies. Lieutenant General Brent Scowcroft (Ret.), Former National Security Advisor, CSIS Counselor and Trustee.)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)(4/11/2012 “Center for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS) Global Security Forum 2012 Scenario 2030: Is the U.S. Nuclear Industry Dying?” http:~/~/csis.org/event/global-security-forum-2012-scenario-2030-us-nuclear-industry-dying)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)MR. HAMRE: Well, Brent, the only place where the wind blows 100 percent of the time is Washington. So I mean, this is the only place you could substitute – (laughter) – nuclear for wind power.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)But let me take you – also, you’re wearing your national security hat – you know, but –

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Going back to Eisenhower, he was trying to find a framework where we would manage the danger of nuclear power but we would still allow its promise for the world. And what – but now we’re in this period where, look, (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__America is going to shrink__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %). I mean – just by very conservative forecast, 20 years from now (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__we’ll__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) probably (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__be down to 50 or 60 plants__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) in America, and (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__the rest of the world is going to build__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) probably (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__200__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %). So there’ll be about 600 plants in the world, 10 percent of them anyways. And if you go out another 20 years, it’s probably going to be 2 percent in the U.S. How does America shape the security environment if this trend continues? How do you think about that, as a former national security advisor?

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)GEN. SCOWCROFT: Well, I think about that a lot. And I didn’t even go to the national security aspects of it, which I think are dominant in a way. (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__We’re going to have a nuclear world. We’re not doing anything.__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) But Saudi Arabia, the homeland of petroleum, is building nuclear plants.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)MR. HAMRE: Nineteen.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)GEN. SCOWCROFT: Most of the world is building nuclear plants now – rapidly. We’re not. The national security aspect of nuclear weapons – of nuclear energy is also extremely important.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)And (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__is there a way__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) that (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__we can spread nuclear power for its benefits and control the resulting capability to go to nuclear weapons,__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) which is a world we’re trying to avoid right now. And that’s a difficult question, especially (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__if we are not in the nuclear power business; then we lose all of our ability to control the development of nuclear energy around the world__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) in a way (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__which provides the benefits__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) of nuclear energy (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__without the detriment of weaponization__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %).

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
MR. HAMRE: You know, if by 2050 we’re down to two nuclear power plants, it’s going to be hard to tell China with 150 how they ought to behave with nuclear power.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== The plan addresses prolif in two ways ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== First, strong nuclear industry: ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== The US nuclear industry is in decline – reviving it is key to set the global standard for nuclear expansion and restore nonproliferation credibility ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**Wallace and Williams 12 **(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)(Michael Wallace comes to CSIS from Constellation Energy, where he served as vice chairman and COO. During his nine years at Constellation Energy, he led many company business activities, including the formation and operation of two joint ventures with EDF related to nuclear energy. Prior to joining Constellation Energy, he was cofounder and managing director of Barrington Energy Partners, LLC, a strategic consulting firm specializing in energy industry transactions and advisory services. Sarah J. Williams is program coordinator and research associate in the U.S. Nuclear Energy Project at CSIS. Prior to joining CSIS, she was a Herbert Scoville Jr. peace fellow and program coordinator at the Center for Science, Technology and Security Policy at the American Association for the Advancement of Science (AAAS).)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)(4/17/12 “Nuclear Energy in America: Preventing its Early Demise” http:~/~/csis.org/files/publication/120417_gf_wallace_williams.pdf)

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Meanwhile, China, India, Russia, and (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__other countries are looking to significantly expand__(%%) their (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__nuclear energy__(%%) commitments. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__By 2016, China could have 50__(%%) nuclear power (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__plants in operation__(%%), compared with only 14 in 2011. India could add 8 new plants and Russia 10 in the same time frame. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__These trends are expected to accelerate__(%%) out to 2030, by which time China, India, and Russia could account for nearly 40 percent of global nuclear generating capacity.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Meanwhile, several smaller nations, mostly in Asia and the Middle East, are planning to get into the nuclear energy business for the first time. In all, as many as 15 new nations could have this technology within the next two decades. Meanwhile, America’s share of global nuclear generation is expected to shrink, from about 25 percent today to about 14 percent in 2030, and—if current trends continue—to less than 10 percent by mid-century.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__With the center of gravity for__(%%) global (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__nuclear investment shifting__(%%) to a new set of players, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__the U__(%%)nited (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__S__(%%)tates and the international community (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__face__(%%) a difficult set of (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__challenges: stemming the spread of__(%%) nuclear (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__weapons-usable materials and know-how__(%%); preventing further catastrophic nuclear accidents; (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__providing for safe__(%%), long-term nuclear (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__waste management__(%%); and protecting U.S. energy security and economic competitiveness. In this context, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__federal action to reverse the__(%%) American (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__nuclear industry’s impending decline is__(%%) a national security (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__imperative__(%%). The United States cannot afford to become irrelevant in a new nuclear age.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Our nation’s commercial nuclear industry, its military nuclear capabilities, and its strong regulatory institutions can be seen as three legs of a stool. All three legs are needed to support America’s future prosperity and security and to shape an international environment that is conducive to our long-term interests.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__Three__(%%) specific (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__aspects of U.S. leadership are__(%%) particularly (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__important__(%%).

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
First, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__managing the__(%%) national and (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__global security risks associated with the spread of nuclear tech__(%%)nology to countries that don’t necessarily share the same perspective on issues of nonproliferation and nuclear security or may lack the resources to implement effective safeguards in this area. An approach that relies on (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__influence__(%%) and involvement (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__through a viable domestic industry is likely to be more effective__(%%) and less expensive (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__than trying to contain__(%%) these (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__risks militarily__(% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %).

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Second, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__setting global norms and standards for safety__(%%), security, operations, and emergency response. As the world learned with past nuclear accidents and more recently with Fukushima, a major accident anywhere can have lasting repercussions everywhere. As with nonproliferation and security, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__America’s ability to exert leadership and influence__(%%) in this area (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__is directly linked to the strength of our domestic industry and__(%%) our (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__active involvement in__(%%) the global (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__nuclear enterprise.__(%%) A strong domestic civilian industry and regulatory structure have immediate national security significance in that they help support the nuclear capabilities of the U.S. Navy, national laboratories, weapons complex, and research institutions.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Third, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__in the past, the__(%%) U.S. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__government could exert influence by striking export agreements with countries whose__(%%) regulatory and legal (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__frameworks reflected__(%%) and were consistent with (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__our__(%%) own (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__nonproliferation standards__(%%) and commitments. At the same time, our nation set the global standard for effective, independent safety regulation (in the form of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission), led international efforts to reduce proliferation risks (through the 1970 NPT Treaty and other initiatives), and provided a model for industry self-regulation.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
The results were not perfect, but (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__America’s__(%%) institutional (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__support__(%%) for global nonproliferation goals and the regulatory behaviors it modeled clearly (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__helped shape the way nuclear tech__(%%)nology (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__was__(%%) adopted and (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__used__(%%) elsewhere (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__around the world. This influence seems certain to wane if the U__(%%)nited (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__S__(%%)tates (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__is no longer a major__(%%) supplier or (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__user of nuclear tech__(%%)nology. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__With existing nonproliferation__(%%) and safety and security (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__regimes looking increasingly inadequate__(%%) in this rapidly changing global nuclear landscape, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__American leadership and leverage is **more important**__(%%) and more central to our national security interests (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__**than ever.**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
To maintain its leadership role in the development, design, and operation of a growing global nuclear energy infrastructure, the next administration, whether Democrat or Republican, must recognize the invaluable role played by the commercial U.S. nuclear industry and take action to prevent its early demise.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== Second, spread of SMRs: ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== SMRs eliminate the incentive for countries to develop nuclear enrichment knowledge and capacity. ====

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Ioannis (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:1.0em;&amp;#34; %)**Kessides**(%%), Chief Economist for the Development Research Group @ World Bank, (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:1.0em;&amp;#34; %)**and**(%%) Vladimir (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:1.0em;&amp;#34; %)**Kuznetsov**(%%), Consultant for the World Bank, July 20(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:1.0em;&amp;#34; %)**12 **(%%)(“Small Modular Reactors for Enhancing Energy Security in Developing Countries.” http:~/~/www.mdpi.com/2071-1050/4/8/1806/htm)

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
One of the key concerns regarding nuclear deployment in developing countries is that those countries generally have a less mature regulatory regime in place compared to the advanced industrial countries. These considerations place very stringent requirements on power station reliability and safety performance. The need for enhanced levels of safety can be more easily met by SMRs with design options that maximize the use of inherent and passive safety features and incorporate additional layers of “defense in depth” [13]. These safety features can be more easily and effectively implemented in SMRs because of these reactors’ larger surface-to-volume ratio, reduced core power density, lower source term, and less frequent (multi-year) refueling. For example, large surface-to-volume ratios facilitate the passive (with no external source of electrical power or stored energy) removal of decay heat. The extent to which nuclear power will prove an acceptable and enduring option for meeting the future energy requirements worldwide will depend in part upon the ability of the international community to minimize the associated proliferation risks. A major (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__nuclear expansion__(%%) program, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__unless__(%%) is (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__accompanied by__(%%) adequate (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__technical__(%%) and institutional (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__safeguards, could__(%%) increase the risk that weapons-usable fissile materials, facilities, technology, or expertise might be diverted or stolen. The common fear is that such an expansion will (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__make it easier for countries to acquire tech__(%%)nology (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__as a precursor to developing__(%%) nuclear (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__weapons capability or for terrorist groups to obtain nuclear materials. This risk could be__(%%) further (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__compounded by__(%%) the likelihood that (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__plutonium-fueled breeder reactors__(%%) will be widely used to stretch uranium resources (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__under expanded nuclear power deployment__(%%). Enhanced capacity and institutional arrangements to prevent proliferation and diversion of nuclear technology to non-peaceful purposes are challenges that will need to be overcome if nuclear energy is to be expanded in developing countries (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__One__(%%) potential (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__way of mitigating__(%%) the (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__prolif__(%%)eration (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__risks__(%%) of expanded nuclear deployment in developing countries (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__might be through__(%%) the adoption of hub-and-spoke configurations that restrict all sensitive activities (such as isotope separation of uranium or reprocessing of spent fuel) to large, international/regional energy parks that would export fuel, hydrogen, and even (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__small__(%%) (40–50 megawatts) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__sealed reactors__(%%) to client states [30,31]. These reactors would be assembled and fueled at the central nuclear park, sealed ((% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__so that individual fuel assemblies could not be removed__(%%)) and delivered as a unit to the power plant cites of client countries. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__At the end of their core life__(%%) (say 15–20 years) the (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__reactors would be returned __(%%)to the central park (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__unopened__(%%). Thus, during the 15–20 years of operation (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__there would be no refueling and__(%%) consequently the (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__client countries would need no fuel fabrication facilities__(%%) and management capabilities. To the extent that such (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__modular reactors would operate almost autonomously, the hub-and-spoke architecture could reduce substantially the rationale and opportunities for countries to develop __(%%)nuclear research (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__laboratories and train__(%%) technical specialists and (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__scientists whose know-how could later be diverted to weapons activities__(%%) [32]. It should be noted that providing attractive alternatives to the buildup of indigenous facilities is a good idea. However, trying to restrict knowledge diffusion is arguable futile and non-sustainable.

(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== SMRs make covert efforts at prolif incredibly obvious – ensures international response. ====

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Harold (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:1.0em;&amp;#34; %)**Feiveson**(%%), Senior Research Policy Analyst @ Program on Science and Global Security at Princeton, (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:1.0em;&amp;#34; %)**et al.**(%%) Alexander Glaser, Asst Prof. at Woodrow Wilson School of Public Affairs @ Princeton, Marvin Miller, Senior Scientist Emeritus @ MIT Center for International Studies, and Lawrence Scheinman, International Policy @ Monterey Institute of International Studies, 200(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:1.0em;&amp;#34; %)**8**(%%) (http:~/~/www.cissm.umd.edu/papers/files/future_nuclear_power.pdf)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)With respect to country proliferation:

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
• (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__Any country with__(%%) nuclear power and a (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__nuclear power infrastructure could get fissile material__(%%) if it wished – within months or a year – (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__barring international action__(%%) to prevent this. If it had a commercial reactor, it could build a reprocessing plant to separate out plutonium; or it could build a dedicated reactor and reprocessing plant in a somewhat longer period. It could also enrich uranium over time, but as long as the country did not have any enrichment facilities to begin with, such a route would take longer than would a plutonium path. • However, in the scenarios considered, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__it should be possible to have a__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__safeguards regime such that any diversion__(%%) of facilities and materials(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__would be quickly detected, giving time for an international response__(%%) (see the following bullet). In this respect, the once-through fuel cycle, the hub-spoke arrangements with__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)sealed reactors(%%)__, and possibly certain thorium cycles (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__appear__(%%) particularly (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__attractive in making immediately visible an attempted diversion and lengthening the time for a diversion to be consummated__(%%). • Since technically most countries will be able to get nuclear weapons, enforcement and compliance provisions of any international control regime are crucial. • Compliance will be stronger and more accepted if nuclear power is nondiscriminatory. That is, for example, if countries such as the United States wish to have breeder reactors, it will be hard to argue that other countries should not be allowed these. • Secondly, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__compliance will be__(%%) surer and (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__more effective if ventures to produce fissile material__(%%) for weapons (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__can quickly be seen and monitored__(%%) by multinational or international authorities (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__and if the acquisition of__(%%) significant quantities of (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__fissile material__(%%) by a country, clandestinely or overtly, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__will take__(%%) months or (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__longer__(%%). For this reason, we believe that all “sensitive” or “dangerous” nuclear facilities should ideally be put under multinational or international control. This includes reprocessing and enrichment plants. It might include also all uranium mining and milling and spent fuel. In time, the fuel could be “owned” by an international authority.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.3in; margin-right: 0.3in; margin-bottom: 0in; widows: 0; orphans: 0&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif&amp;#34; %)International norms and response solve proliferation – empirics prove.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.3in; margin-right: 0.3in; margin-bottom: 0in; widows: 0; orphans: 0&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**Reed ’10**(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %), [Alexander R. Reed, Master of Arts in Security Studies from Georgetown University, April 14, 2010 “The Role of Denial in Nuclear Nonproliferation,” (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; color: rgb(0, 0, 0)&amp;#34; %)[[https:~~/~~/repository.library.georgetown.edu/bitstream/handle/10822/553565/reedAlexander.pdf?sequence=1&amp;#62;&amp;#62;url:https://repository.library.georgetown.edu/bitstream/handle/10822/553565/reedAlexander.pdf?sequence=1]](% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)]

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__Incentives for integration with the international community benefitted nonproliferation¶ Incentives for normalization__(%%) also (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__played significant roles in__(%%) some of the nonproliferation ¶ successes studied. (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__Libya, South Africa, and Brazi__(%%)__l (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)all sought increased integration(%%)__ ¶ within the international community, (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__but had to forgo their nuclear weapons programs__(%%) ¶ before such integration could occur. South Africa, long isolated due to its policy of¶ apartheid, sought to establish a cooperative relationship with international (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)¶ (%%)community.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)¶ (%%)137(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)¶ (%%)While eliminating apartheid was the biggest step, South Africa also had ¶ to renounce its nuclear weapons. The (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__sanctions and isolation imposed by the ¶ international community__(%%) against apartheid thus (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__had a significant effect on South __Africa(%%)’s ¶ nuclear weapons motivations.__ (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)Brazil(%%)__ similarly wanted to integrate into the international ¶ community. The Brazilian Government initially saw nuclear weapons as a means to ¶ increase its prestige among global powers.¶ 138¶ When the civilian government took ¶ control, however, it (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__saw nuclear weapons as an obstacle to unrestricted membership__(%%) ¶ and leadership in the international community.¶ 139¶ (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__Brazil chose to renounce its weapons ¶ programs and alleviate international pressure__(%%) to help accomplish that central goal.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== Prolif causes extinction. ====

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Heisbourg ’12, [Francois Heisbourg, Chairman of the International Institute for Strategic Studies, prof at the Geneva Center for Security Policy, July 2012, “How Bad Would the Further Spread of Nuclear Weapons Be?”, [[http:~~/~~/www.npolicy.org/userfiles/file/oving%20Beyond%20Pretense%20web%20version.pdf#page=182&amp;#62;&amp;#62;url:http://www.npolicy.org/userfiles/file/oving%20Beyond%20Pretense%20web%20version.pdf#page=182]]]

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__Human societies__(%%) tend to (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__lack the imagination to think through__(%%), and to act upon, what have become known as (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__“black swan” events__(%%) 26 : (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__That which has never occurred__(%%) (or which has happened very rarely and in a wholly different context) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__is deemed not__(%%) to be (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__in the field of reality__(% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %)__,__(%%) and to which must be added eventualities that are denied because their consequences are too awful to contemplate. The extremes of human misconduct (the incredulity in the face of evidence of the Holocaust, the failure to imagine 9/11) bear testimony to this hardwired trait of our species. This would not normally warrant mention as a factor of growing salience if not for the recession into time of the original and only use of nuclear weapons in August 1945. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__Nonuse of nuclear weapons may soon be taken for granted__(%%) rather than being an absolute taboo. Recent writing on the reputedly limited effects of the Hiroshima and Nagasaki bombs 27 may contribute to such a trend, in the name of reducing the legitimacy of nuclear weapons. Recent, and often compelling, historical accounts of the surrender of the Japanese Empire that downplay the role of the atomic bombings in comparison to early research can produce a similar effect, even if that may not have been the intention. 28 However desirable it has been, the end of atmospheric nuclear testing 29 has removed for more than three decades the periodic reminders that such monstrous detonations made as to the uniquely destructive nature of nuclear weapons. There is a real and growing risk that we forget what was obvious to those who first described in 1941 the unique nature of yet-to-be produced nuclear weapons. 30 The risk is no doubt higher in those states for which the history of World War II has little relevance and that have not had the will or the opportunity to wrestle at the time or ex post facto with the moral and strategic implications of the nuclear bombing of Japan in 1945. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__Unsustainable strains are__(%%) possibly (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__the single most compelling feature of contemporary proliferation__(% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %)__.__(%%) Examples include (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__tight geographical constraints__(%%)__–__with, for instance, New Delhi and Islamabad, located within 300 miles of each other; nuclear multi-polarity against the backdrop of multiple, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__crisscrossing sources of tension in the Middle East, as opposed to the relative simplicity of the U.S.-Soviet confrontation__(%%); the existence of doctrines, such as India’s “cold start,” and (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__force postures__(%%), such as Pakistan’s broadening array of battle- field nukes, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__that rest on the expectation of early use; and the role of non-state actors as aggravating or triggering factors when they are perceived as operating with__(%%) the connivance of (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__an antagonist state__(%%) (in the past, the assassination of the Austrian Archduke in Sarajevo in 1914; and in the future, Hezbollah operatives launching rockets with effect against Israel or Lashkar-e-Taiba commandos doing a “Bombay” redux in India?). (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__Individually or in combination, these factors test crisis management capabilities more severely than anything__(%%) seen (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__during the Cold War__(%%) with the partial exception of the Cuban Missile Crisis. Even the overabundant battlefield nuclear arsenals in Cold War Central Europe, with their iffy weapons’ safety and security arrangements, were less of a challenge: The U.S. and Soviet short-range nuclear weapons so deployed were not putting U.S. and Soviet territory and capitals at risk. It may be argued that these risk factors are known to potential protagonists and that they therefore will be led to avoid the sort of nuclear brinksmanship that characterized U.S. and Soviet behavior during the Cold War in crises such as the Korean War, Berlin, Cuba or the Yom Kippur War. Unfortunately, the multiple nuclear crises between India and Pakistan demonstrate no such prudence, rather the contrary. And were such restraint to feed into nuclear policy and crisis planning, along the lines of apparently greater U.S. and Soviet nuclear caution from the mid-seventies onwards, the fact would remain that (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__initial intent rarely resists the strains of a complex, multiactor confrontation between inherently distrustful antagonists__(%%). It is also worth reflecting on the fact that during the 1980s there was real and acute fear in Soviet ruling circles that the West was preparing an out-of-the-blue nuclear strike, a fear which in turn fed into Soviet policies and dispositions. 31 The Cold War was a set of crises and misunderstandings that came within a whisker of a nuclear holocaust. India and Pakistan’s nuclear ¶ standoff is deeply unstable, not least as a result of the interaction with non-state actors.(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__ A multipolar nuclear Middle East would make ¶ the Cuban Missile Crisis look easy in comparison__(% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %)__.__

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== (% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Times New Roman, serif;&amp;#34; %)Proliferation causes nuclear deterrence to fail. Impossible to replicate Cold War stability.(%%) ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.3in; margin-right: 0.3in; margin-bottom: 0in; widows: 0; orphans: 0&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**Shultz et al. ’11**(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %), George P. Shultz, former secretary of state, William J. Perry, former secretary of defense, Henry A. Kissinger, former secretary of state, and Sam Nunn, former chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee, 04-07-2011“Deterrence in an Age of Nuclear Deterrence”, (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; color: rgb(0, 0, 0)&amp;#34; %)[[http:~~/~~/www.nonukes.nl/media/files/2011-03-07-gang-of-four-tnw.pdf&amp;#62;&amp;#62;url:http://www.nonukes.nl/media/files/2011-03-07-gang-of-four-tnw.pdf]]

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.3in; margin-right: 0.3in; margin-bottom: 0in; widows: 0; orphans: 0&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__As long as there has been war, there have been efforts to deter__ actions a nation considers¶ threatening. Until fairly recently, this meant building a military establishment capable of¶ intimidating the adversary, defeating him or making his victory more costly than the projected¶ gains. This, with conventional weapons, took time. Deterrence and war strategy were identical.¶ (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__The advent of the nuclear weapon introduced __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__**entirely new factors**__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__.__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) It was possible, for the first¶ time, to inflict at the beginning of a war the maximum casualties. The doctrine of mutual¶ assured destruction represented this reality. Deterrence based on nuclear weapons, therefore,¶ has three elements:

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.3in; margin-right: 0.3in; margin-bottom: 0in; widows: 0; orphans: 0&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color:#000000;&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)It is importantly psychological, depending on calculations for which there is no historical¶ experience. It is therefore precarious.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.3in; margin-right: 0.3in; margin-bottom: 0in; widows: 0; orphans: 0&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color:#000000;&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)It is devastating. An unrestrained nuclear exchange between superpowers could destroy¶ civilized life as we know it in days.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.3in; margin-right: 0.3in; margin-bottom: 0in; widows: 0; orphans: 0&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color:#000000;&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__Mutual assured destruction raises enormous inhibitions against employing the weapons__.¶ Since the first use of nuclear weapons against Japan, neither of the superpowers, nor any other¶ country, has used nuclear weapons in a war. A gap opened between the psychological element¶ of deterrence and the risks most leaders were willing to incur. U.S. defense leaders made¶ serious efforts to give the president more flexible options for nuclear use short of global¶ annihilation. They never solved the problem, and it was always recognized that Washington¶ and Moscow both held the keys to unpredictable and potentially catastrophic escalations.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.3in; margin-right: 0.3in; margin-bottom: 0in; widows: 0; orphans: 0&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)As a result, nuclear deterrence was useful in preventing only the most catastrophic scenarios¶ that would have threatened our survival. But (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__even with the deployment of thousands of nuclear¶ weapons__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) on both sides of the Iron Curtain, the (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__Soviet moves into Hungary in 1956 and¶ Czechoslovakia in 1968 were not deterred. Nor were__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ the numerous crises involving Berlin,¶ including the building of the Wall in 1961, or __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__major wars in Korea and Vietnam, or the Soviet¶ invasion of Afghanistan__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ in 1979__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**.**(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) In the case of the Soviet Union, nuclear weapons did not¶ prevent collapse or regime change.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.3in; margin-right: 0.3in; margin-bottom: 0in; widows: 0; orphans: 0&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Today, the Cold War is almost 20 years behind us, but many leaders and publics cannot¶ conceive of deterrence without a strategy of mutual assured destruction. We have written¶ (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)previously that (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__reliance on this strategy is becoming increasingly hazardous. With the spread of¶ nuclear weapons, tech__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)nology, (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__materials and know__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Cambria Math serif; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__‐__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Cambria Math serif; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__how, there is an increasing risk that nuclear¶ weapons will be used__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__.__

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.3in; margin-right: 0.3in; margin-bottom: 0in; widows: 0; orphans: 0&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__It is not possible to replicate the high__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Cambria Math serif; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__‐__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Cambria Math serif; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__risk stability that prevailed between the two nuclear¶ superpowers__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ during the Cold War in such an environment. __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Cambria Math serif; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__The growing number of nations¶ with nuclear arms__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ and differing motives, aims and ambitions __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Cambria Math serif; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__poses very high and¶ unpredictable risks and increased instability.__

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.3in; margin-right: 0.3in; margin-bottom: 0in; widows: 0; orphans: 0&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__From 1945 to 1991, America and the Soviet Union were diligent, professional, but also lucky¶ that nuclear weapons were never used. __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__Does the world want to continue to bet its survival on¶ continued good fortune__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ with a growing number of nuclear nations and adversaries globally?¶__ Can we devise and successfully implement with other nations, including other nuclear powers,¶ careful, cooperative concepts to safely dismount the nuclear tiger while strengthening the¶ capacity to assure our security and that of allies and other countries considered essential to our¶ national security?

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== Global nuclear leadership solves nuclear terrorism – uniformity key to create regime for material protection ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**Brill and Luongo 12**(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) (Kenneth C. Brill is a former U.S. ambassador to the I.A.E.A.Kenneth N. Luongo is president of the Partnership for Global Security. Both are members of the Fissile Material Working Group, a nonpartisan nongovernmental organization.)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)(3/15/12 Nuclear Terrorism: A Clear Danger. http:~/~/www.nytimes.com/2012/03/16/opinion/nuclear-terrorism-a-clear-danger.html)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Terrorists exploit gaps in security. (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__The current__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) global (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__regime for protecting__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) the(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__nuclear materials__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) that terrorists desire for their ultimate weapon is far from seamless. It (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__is based__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) largely (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__on unaccountable__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %), voluntary (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__arrangements that are inconsistent__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)across borders. Its (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__weak links make it dangerous and inadequate__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) to prevent nuclear terrorism.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Later this month in Seoul, the more than 50 world leaders who will gather for the second Nuclear Security Summit need to seize the opportunity to start developing an accountable regime to prevent nuclear terrorism.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__There is a consensus__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) among international leaders (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__that the threat of nuclear terrorism is real__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %),(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) not a Hollywood confection. President Obama, the leaders of 46 other nations, the heads of the International Atomic Energy Agency and the United Nations, and numerous experts have called nuclear terrorism one of the most serious threats to global security and stability. It is also preventable with more aggressive action.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__At least four__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) terrorist (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__groups, including Al Qaeda, have demonstrated interest in using a nuclear device. These groups operate in__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) or near(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__states with__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) histories of(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__questionable nuclear security__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__practices__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %). (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__Terrorists do not need to steal a__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) nuclear (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__weapon. It is__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) quite (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__possible to make an improvised__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) nuclear (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__device from__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) highly enriched (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__uranium__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) or plutonium being used (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__for civilian purposes.__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) And there is a black market in such material. There have been 18 confirmed thefts or loss of weapons-usable nuclear material. In 2011, the Moldovan police broke up part of a smuggling ring attempting to sell highly enriched uranium; one member is thought to remain at large with a kilogram of this material.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)__A terrorist nuclear explosion could kill hundreds of thousands, create billions of dollars in damages and undermine the global economy.__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) Former Secretary General Kofi Annan of the United Nations said that (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)__an act of nuclear terrorism “would thrust tens of millions of people into dire poverty”__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) and create “a second death toll throughout the developing world.”

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Surely after such an event, global leaders would produce a strong global system to ensure nuclear security. There is no reason to wait for a catastrophe to build such a system.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)__The conventional wisdom is that domestic regulations__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %), U.N. Security Council resolutions, G-8 initiatives, I.A.E.A. activities and other voluntary efforts (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)__will prevent nuclear terrorism. But existing global arrangements__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) for nuclear security (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)__lack uniformity and coherence__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %).

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)There are no globally agreed standards for effectively securing nuclear material(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)__. There is no obligation to follow the voluntary standards that do exist __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)and no institution, not even the I.A.E.A., with a mandate to evaluate nuclear security performance.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)This patchwork approach provides the appearance of dealing with nuclear security; the reality is there are gaps through which a determined terrorist group could drive one or more nuclear devices.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Obama’s initiative in launching the nuclear security summit process in Washington in 2010 helped focus high-level attention on nuclear security issues. Unfortunately, the actions produced by the 2010 Washington Summit and that are planned for the upcoming Seoul Summit are voluntary actions that are useful, but not sufficient to create an effective global nuclear security regime.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)The world cannot afford to wait for the patchwork of nuclear security arrangements to fail before they are strengthened. Instead, (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__we need a system based on a global framework__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) convention on nuclear security (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__that would fill the gaps in existing voluntary arrangements.__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)This framework convention would commit states to an effective standard of nuclear security practices, incorporate relevant existing international agreements, and give the I.A.E.A. the mandate to support nuclear security by evaluating whether states are meeting their nuclear security obligations and providing assistance to those states that need help in doing so.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)__Nuclear terrorism is a real and present danger for all states,__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) not just a few. Preventing it is an achievable goal. The current focus on nuclear security through voluntary actions, however, is not commensurate with either the risk or consequences of nuclear terrorism. (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)__This must be rectified__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %). If the Seoul Nuclear Security Summit makes this a priority, there can be an effective global nuclear security regime in place before this decade ends.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== Terrorism results in nuclear great power war ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)**Ayson 10**(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)**,**(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) Professor of Strategic Studies and Director of the Centre for Strategic Studies: New Zealand at the Victoria University of Wellington, 2010 (Robert,“After a Terrorist Nuclear Attack: Envisaging Catalytic Effects,” (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)//Studies in Conflict and Terrorism//(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %), Volume 33, Issue 7, July, Available Online to Subscribing Institutions via InformaWorld)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; lang=&amp;#34;en-US&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.3in; margin-right: 0.3in; margin-bottom: 0in; widows: 0; orphans: 0&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)But these two nuclear worlds—a non-state actor nuclear attack and a catastrophic interstate nuclear exchange—are not necessarily separable. It is just possible that some sort of terrorist attack, and especially an act of (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__nuclear terrorism, could precipitate a chain of events leading to a massive exchange of nuclear weapons between two or more of the states__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) that possess them. In this context, today’s and tomorrow’s terrorist groups might assume the place allotted during the early Cold War years to new state possessors of small nuclear arsenals who were seen as raising the risks of a catalytic nuclear warbetween the superpowersstarted by third parties. These risks were considered in the late 1950s and early 1960s as concerns grew about nuclear proliferation, the so-called n+1 problem. It may require a considerable amount of imagination to depict an especially plausible situation where an act of nuclear terrorism could lead to such a massive inter-state nuclear war. For example, in the event of a terrorist nuclear attack on the United States, it might well be wondered just how Russia and/or China could plausibly be brought into the picture, not least because they seem unlikely to be fingered as the most obvious state sponsors or encouragers of terrorist groups. They would seem far too responsible to be involved in supporting that sort of terrorist behavior that could just as easily threaten them as well. Some possibilities, however remote, do suggest themselves. For example, how might the United States react if it was thought or discovered that the fissile material used in the act of nuclear terrorism had come from Russian stocks,40 and if for some reason Moscow denied any responsibility for nuclear laxity? The correct attribution of that nuclear material to a particular country might not be a case of science fiction given the observation by Michael May et al. that while the debris resulting from a nuclear explosion would be “spread over a wide area in tiny fragments, its radioactivity makes it detectable, identifiable and collectable, and a wealth of information can be obtained from its analysis: the efficiency of the explosion, the materials used and, most important … some indication of where the nuclear material came from.”41 Alternatively, if the act of nuclear terrorism came as a complete surprise, and American officials refused to believe that a terrorist group was fully responsible (or responsible at all) suspicion would shift immediately to state possessors. Ruling out Western ally countries like the United Kingdom and France, and probably Israel and India as well, authorities in Washington would be left with a very short list consisting of North Korea, perhaps Iran if its program continues, and possibly Pakistan. But at what stage would Russia and China be definitely ruled out in this high stakes game of nuclear Cluedo? In particular, if the act of nuclear terrorism occurred against a backdrop of existing tension in Washington’s relations with Russia and/or China, and at a time when threats had already been traded between these major powers, (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__would__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) officials and political (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__leaders not__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) be tempted to (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__assume the worst__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)__?__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) Of course, the chances of this occurring would only seem to increase if the United States was already involved in some sort of limited armed conflict with Russia and/or China, or if they were confronting each other from a distance in a proxy war, as unlikely as these developments may seem at the present time. The reverse might well apply too: should a nuclear terrorist attack occur in Russia or China during a period of heightened tension or even limited conflict with the United States, could Moscow and Beijing resist the pressures that might rise domestically to consider the United States as a possible perpetrator or encourager of the attack? (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__Washington’s early response to a terrorist nuclear attack on its own soil mi__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__ght__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) also (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font